      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 3,\n  \"summary\": \"All three review-2 items (W1 zeroclaw coverage, W2 whitespace dict token, B2 bare-string whitespace) are correctly addressed. The six new tests are structurally sound and cover the stated requirements. Two warnings remain: substring-based JSON assertions in the parametrized acceptance test are brittle against future baseline changes, and a NUL-only dict token (`{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"\\\\x00\\\"}`) silently collapses to empty auth instead of raising — inconsistent with the whitespace-only case that does raise — and is untested.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py:1371-1372\",\n      \"issue\": \"Substring assertions for JSON structure: `assert f'\\\"token\\\": \\\"{expected_token}\\\"' in json_body` and `assert '\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\"' in json_body` validate presence anywhere in the document, not at `gateway.auth.token` specifically. The baseline openclaw.json has no `\\\"token\\\"` key today, so there is no current false-positive risk — but if the baseline ever gains one (e.g., in `session.threadBindings` or a future `auth` variant block), both assertions would pass even if `_render_openclaw_json` wrote the token to the wrong path. The NUL-in-dict-token parametrize case (`expected_token = \\\"deadbeefcafef00dtail\\\"`) is the most exposed because its token is produced by stripping, so any path mismatch regression would be invisible.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Replace substring checks with structured JSON parsing: `import json; data = json.loads(json_body); assert data[\\\"gateway\\\"][\\\"auth\\\"][\\\"token\\\"] == expected_token; assert data[\\\"gateway\\\"][\\\"auth\\\"][\\\"mode\\\"] == \\\"token\\\"`. This is a one-liner change per assertion and pins the actual key path against future baseline evolution.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py:1389-1412 (missing case) + src/clawrium/core/render.py:608\",\n      \"issue\": \"NUL-only and NUL+whitespace dict-token cases are not tested and behave inconsistently with the stated semantics. Python's `str.strip()` does NOT remove NUL (\\\\x00 is not in the whitespace set). So `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"\\\\x00\\\"}` passes the guard at render.py:608 (`not token.strip()` → `not \\\"\\\\x00\\\"` → False), then `_clean_secret` strips the NUL to `\\\"\\\"`, then `.strip()` yields `\\\"\\\"` → `gateway.auth = \\\"\\\"` → no auth block in JSON. The net behaviour (empty auth, no block) is the same as the whitespace-only case, but the path is different: the whitespace-only case raises `AgentConfigError` while the NUL-only case silently degrades. A `{\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"\\\\x00   \\\"}` token similarly bypasses the guard because `\\\"\\\\x00   \\\".strip()` = `\\\"\\\\x00\\\"` (truthy). This is an untested inconsistency in the #437 gateway-token invariant defence.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add two cases to `test_gateway_auth_rejects_malformed_shapes`: `({\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"\\\\x00\\\"}, \\\"missing or empty 'token'\\\")` and `({\\\"mode\\\": \\\"token\\\", \\\"token\\\": \\\"\\\\x00   \\\"}, \\\"missing or empty 'token'\\\")`. To make them pass, the production guard at render.py:608 needs to account for NUL: change `not token.strip()` to `not token.replace(\\\"\\\\x00\\\", \\\"\\\").strip()` (or reuse `_clean_secret(token).strip()`). The current NUL-in-real-token acceptance case (`_AUTH_TOKEN_820 + \\\"\\\\x00tail\\\"`) is unaffected because the real content survives NUL-stripping.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py:1480-1481\",\n      \"issue\": \"`test_gateway_auth_dict_shape_works_for_zeroclaw` asserts only `\\\".zeroclaw/config.toml\\\" in rendered.files`. While the zeroclaw Jinja template is confirmed to not reference `gateway.auth` (grep returns no matches), the test provides no negative pin against a future template change that leaks a raw-dict form or the bare token into the TOML. A render-success assertion is the weakest possible form for a security-adjacent test.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Extend to assert: (1) the rendered TOML body does not contain the literal string `mode` as a gateway property (which would indicate dict leakage), and (2) add `import tomllib; tomllib.loads(toml_body)` to confirm the TOML is parseable — a dict object leaking into a TOML string context would typically produce a `{...}` literal that breaks the TOML parser.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/core/test_render.py:1303-1327 (_openclaw_stores_with_auth)\",\n      \"issue\": \"The helper sets `default_model: \\\"m\\\"` (a single-character string), which exercises the empty-model guard at render.py:1500 (non-empty passes). This is fine for #820 coverage, but if a future test accidentally reuses this helper with a provider type requiring a non-trivial model prefix (e.g., litellm), `\\\"m\\\"` would produce `\\\"lt/m\\\"` as the model ID with no breakage signal. No action required; just noting the intentional narrowness of the fixture.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"No immediate change needed. Consider naming the fixture constant `_STUB_MODEL = \\\"m\\\"` to make its role as a stub value explicit, distinct from real model IDs.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Fix the NUL-only dict-token guard at render.py:608: change `not token.strip()` to `not _clean_secret(token).strip()` so NUL-only and NUL+whitespace tokens are caught by the same raise path as whitespace-only tokens, then add corresponding parametrize cases to `test_gateway_auth_rejects_malformed_shapes`.\",\n    \"Replace the two substring JSON assertions at test_render.py:1371-1372 with `json.loads(json_body)[\\\"gateway\\\"][\\\"auth\\\"][\\\"token\\\"]` structural checks.\",\n    \"Confirm review-2 sign-off: W1 (zeroclaw dict shape) covered by `test_gateway_auth_dict_shape_works_for_zeroclaw`, W2 (whitespace dict token) covered by the `\\\"   \\\"` and `\\\"\\\\t\\\\n\\\"` parametrize cases, B2 (bare-string whitespace) covered by `test_gateway_auth_bare_string_whitespace_becomes_empty` — all three are addressed and passing.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 3,\n    \"domain\": \"render-assembly test coverage (#820 gateway auth shape normalization)\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
